{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/domain-expertise-why-is-it-important-for-data-scientists-2d6a406d544d", "time": 1683004285.972574, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/domain-expertise-why-is-it-important-for-data-scientists-2d6a406d544d/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Domain expertise \u2014 why is it important for data scientists? | by Zeming Yu | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Domain expertise \u2014 why is it important for data scientists?", "description": "Domain expertise is the knowledge and understanding of a particular field. As data scientists, you may be working in a wide variety of industries, each of which has its own intricacies that can only\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://www.lexico.com/en/definition/jargon", "anchor_text": "Oxford Dictionary", "paragraph_index": 11}, {"url": "http://kaggle.com", "anchor_text": "kaggle", "paragraph_index": 18}, {"url": "https://www.kaggle.com/c/porto-seguro-safe-driver-prediction/discussion/44629", "anchor_text": "Porto Seguro\u2019s Safe Driver Prediction", "paragraph_index": 20}], "all_paragraphs": ["Domain expertise is the knowledge and understanding of a particular field. As data scientists, you may be working in a wide variety of industries, each of which has its own intricacies that can only be learned gradually over time.", "As a simple illustration, have a look at these groups of words for different industries:", "loss ratio, combined ratio, conversion rate, price elasticity, price optimisation, cross subsidisation, tariff, mix of business, excess, attritional claims", "odds ratio, handicap, long odds, underdog, edge, bookmaker", "orderbook, arbitrage, short, sharpe ratio, volume weighted average price, time weighted average price, alpha, beta", "funnels analysis, cohort analysis, user segmentation, retention analyses, click through rate, recommendation engine", "genomic, clinical/phenotypic, pharmacokinetic, and other molecular data", "Do they look familiar? Can you guess what industry each group of words comes from?", "If the answer is yes, you probably have some domain expertise in that field already!", "(Scroll down to the bottom of this article to find out what industries they are.)", "Note that Group A is the longest list amongst all of them. The reason is simple, I have more domain expertise in that particular industry after spending many years working in it. \ud83d\ude02", "Well, these are just jargons. They are used to make you sound smart in front of people outside your industry, or according to the Oxford Dictionary, they are:", "Special words or expressions that are used by a particular profession or group and are difficult for others to understand.", "These words are indeed difficult for others to understand unless you happen to work in that industry.", "From a communications perspective, all jokes aside, we should avoid using jargon when presenting to outsiders, or at least give it a brief explanation first. Never assume people know what they mean otherwise you are likely to lose their interest very quickly.", "On the other hand, we can also view jargon as highly condensed domain knowledge. For example, behind the two simple words \u201ccombined ratio\u201d, we have these concepts:", "In Industry A, these concepts are used every day by people across the organization (including those in management positions).", "A data scientist who\u2019s never worked in this industry and has no clue about these concepts is likely to have a hard time (at least initially) working effectively. Knowing these concepts helps the data scientist to:", "You may argue that kaggle competitions have been won by people with and without domain knowledge alike.", "If you have domain knowledge, you could do some specific feature engineering that\u2019s relevant to the context of the problem and gain an edge over others.", "On the other hand, you could also (or sometimes have to) discard domain knowledge and adopt a pure software engineering approach and win a competition, especially when the data need to be anonymized, thus preventing the use of domain knowledge. Check out the 1st place winner\u2019s solution to the Porto Seguro\u2019s Safe Driver Prediction.", "However, I believe that the pursuit of pure predictiveness should not the only goal of a data scientist.", "Data science in kaggle is not the same as in the real world. What about defining the business objective? Communicating effectively to the decision-makers? Understanding how the data is collected? These questions have been hidden away from the kaggle competitions, but are very important in the real world when working for an organization.", "Also, consider this. Right now a lot of the data science work involves software development skills, e.g. pure hyperparameter tuning skills. In 5\u201310 years' time, with the improved machine learning infrastructure and the rise of automated machine learning, much of the heavy lifting will disappear.", "What will set apart a great data scientist is domain knowledge \u2014 the ability to demonstrate that you know the industry inside out, that you talk the language and you can help the business to achieve its target by help finding the right business problem to solve.", "Demand for these skills will not go away.", "A: insurance; B: betting; C: quantitative trading D: marketing E: genomics", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F2d6a406d544d&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fdomain-expertise-why-is-it-important-for-data-scientists-2d6a406d544d&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "